This paper deals with geometric complexity theory, which is a subfield of computational complexity theory that uses algebraic geometry to study the complexity of algebraic computations. The paper focuses on the separation of orbit closures via symmetries, which suggests that it could belong to the following sub-categories:

- cs.AG (Algebraic Geometry): This sub-category deals with the study of geometric objects defined by algebraic equations, and geometric complexity theory uses algebraic geometry to study the complexity of algebraic computations. Therefore, cs.AG is also a likely sub-category for this paper.
- cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory): This sub-category deals with the intersection of computer science and game theory, and geometric complexity theory has connections to game theory through the study of the complexity of computing Nash equilibria.
